The last time I listened to ‘In Response’ I sat in Sarah’s car just before we were about to go to dinner and cried my eyes out. I simultaneously laughed my ass off. It makes perfect sense because while This Day Forward essentially started out as a goof, it was one super serious joke. The most meaningful joke ever told if you will.

 It wasn’t that we didn’t take music seriously, in fact music and especially hardcore/punk rock was legitimately sacred to all of us; it was ourselves that we didn’t take serious at all. The initial idea of the band existed within a Venn diagram of seeking joy via music and laughter. This simple combination carried us through the entirety of our creative journey together & still thrives in our friendship today.

We were in high school when we started the band. Like many others we handmade our first cassette demo tapes and played our first show in a living room. By the time I we were in college we had signed two record deals and played all over the country. In the beginning we all saved what we made from our shitty jobs in order to pay for the expenses of tour. Initially we caravanned with 4 cars carrying gear and whatever scrappy merch we had made. Then at some point Mike had a trailer hitch put onto his red Chevy Corsica which I think got us down to two vehicles. (We eventually got our first van in 01 literally hours before leaving for our first full US tour with Taken)

It wasn’t that we didn’t have fans. We did. Quite a few, all things considered,  it’s just that touring is/was expensive as fuck and bands like us never knew our own worth. 

We printed out directions to the shows from Mapquest. We called home using calling cards at pay phones. We didn’t have cell phones until the final year of the band. There was no such thing as social media, no one even promoted shows online yet. Most of the shows we played were based on blind faith that the person who emailed or called us actually followed through and would be there when we showed up to let us in. (hopefully with some people ready to pay $5 & mosh)

(Continued in comments below)

20 Years Ago Today (what an insane thing to say) on June 17th, 2003, This Day Forward released what would be our final album and first and only for Equal Vision Records (@equalvision ), In Response. 

The making of, recording, and touring of In Response was a life-changing time for all of us. We were a small group of high school outsiders who befriended each other through punk and hardcore music and through that community we took a huge life chance and made the most of our youth. 

We chose to follow our dreams while pausing what most would call "real life." It was a magical time and much different from the world we live in now and there's a lot of fondness looking back at everything 20 years later. In Response, to US, is the pinnacle of the band and where the band was destined to go. 

We were always true to ourselves and we thank you all for allowing the music to remain in your lives after all of this time. 

From the bottom of our hearts, thank you for allowing us to live the musical dream. 

There will be more posted... stay tuned.

I’m still recovering from Friday. I’m totally blown away by the amount of love and support I was shown. 

My heart is immensely full. This show took everything out of me over the last 4 months or so which made me less present here as well as IRL but every step of the way I had people reaching out & encouraging me, understanding my limits and helping to fuel me forward.

This show is about my neurodivergent mind. It is about my hearing loss & sudden onset of tinnitus. It is about my life as a medicated (and unmedicated) musician, vagabond, awkward heartbroken outcast. It is a love letter to my fellow neurodivergent people. To disabled people of all kinds. To artists of all kinds. The goal of the show was to make people feel the overwhelm that so many of us feel on a daily basis but more importantly to make those who resonate with this work feel seen, represented and held. I had so many amazing comments on opening night of people saying that they felt something they lacked language for being out on display bringing them catharsis. 

At a time where the world feels most grim, dwarfing the importance of most other things… art & community is always here with us & for us. I’ve never felt more confident in my role here in life. 

Friends, family and collectors traveled by plane, train, bus, car and by foot to show up for me. My amazing wife & partner in life @sarahtheshadowwitch (who’s journey has also deeply inspired my own) has been in full support even when I had to commit 12-14 hour studio days for months on end with no real promise of what it would result in besides a new body of work. She spent all day and night curating arrangement and hanging the show with @colonna_contemporary & I on weds. I love you Sarah. 

I think my biggest takeaway from this show is how fucking lucky I am. My friends, my family, and even my stranger supporters who I don’t know… these people in my life are truly second to none and I feel at times I do not deserve them. Thank you all so much. 

I’ll post some more insights & images though out the week. A lot of works have sold 🙏 please reach out for a list of what’s available or to just see the full catalog.

Homesick I & II. stolen hotel key cards, adhesive on wood panel. 2023. NFS

For as long as I can recall I stole pretty much every hotel key card I’ve ever got my hands on. Being that I spent over 20 years of my life constantly traveling that has added up to a lot of them. Something about them felt potent to me yet also flimsy and meaningless like most plastic. I guess it was the fact that they were electronically charged and coded to the actual room I stayed in felt biographical to me so I kept them always planning on doing something with them. I used a small portion of my stash to create these two works for my show.

these three works are called “Reconstruction of a Former Self I-III”

they are comprised of previous works of mine that I collaged thick layers, partially painted, destroyed and then reconstructed. A metaphorical meditation on time travel, healing/changing the past. 

I & II are SOLD but III is available 🟢

a very simple neurodivergent story told through icons.

This iPod plays one track on infinite repeat and it is the sound of my tinnitus. 

I included the track here for you to observe if you wish. (headphones recommended) Ironically I cannot even hear it unless I put it into my right ear. I had to create it by monitoring it in the right but for accuracy then bouncing it in the left. 

Roughly 2 years ago now I had a sudden onset of asymmetrical tinnitus in my left ear. I simultaneously started having intense bouts of vertigo that ultimately proved to be coincidental occurrences of vestibular migraines. I had numerous tests & scans done, suggesting that this was all nothing more than human wear and tear (no tumor or anything luckily) It’s been a long and bumpy road. To get rid of the vertigo I had to do daily physical therapy exercises over the course of 12 months. 

The tinnitus obviously is permanent unless I get stem cell which is still a very expensive experimental results vary type of situation. I tried a hearing aid and it was terrifyingly strange and uncomfortable. I didn’t even make it out of the parking lot before removing it.

I will say that I’m amazed at how plastic our brains are however. For most of my days I can now ignore the ringing. Mornings and right before bed are still tough and I still have entire days occasionally where I’m struggling with it but for the most part I’m in such a better place with it than I was when it first came on. 

When I was creating the works for A Noisy Mind this was one of the first ideas that really excited me. It was extremely powerful to watch people interact with the piece at the opening. It’s rare that you can create a piece that can so seamlessly allow someone else to experience what it’s like in your head. I have an actual signal that is invisible to anyone around me but now you can just press play and hear what’s there.

Constant Companion. Gesso, Spray Paint, Tinnitus recording with Used iPod Touch on Wood Panel. 2023 NFS
